those who are listening to this

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:06.030
for the first time.

00:07:06.030 --> 00:07:08.200
Let's see what
screen reader is not.

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:14.060
Screen reader is not
a different interface.

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:19.970
Screen reader is not an
operating system, that's obvious,

00:07:19.970 --> 00:07:24.310
and screen reader is not
our accessibility advocate.

00:07:25.470 --> 00:07:26.470
We are.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:34.760
Screen reader is actually a
speech software that converts text

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:35.760
into speech.

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:43.470
Now, there are various screen readers
for different operating systems.

00:07:43.470 --> 00:07:48.880
For example, on Windows, the most
popular ones are JAWS, Commentary.

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:54.180
For Android,
we have Commentary and TalkBack.

00:07:54.180 --> 00:07:57.340
For iOS, there is a VoiceOver,
and so on and so forth.

00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:06.340
However, to enjoy all the
things of what screen reader has

00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:13.090
to offer, its users must
understand and must remember

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:19.550
many keyboard shortcuts that are
associated with screen reader only.

00:08:19.550 --> 00:08:23.210
For example,
if your screen reader is turned on,

00:08:23.210 --> 00:08:30.680
and you press Insert F7, you are
most likely bring the list of links

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:31.830
on that web page.

00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:39.200
On the other hand,
if your screen reader is turned off

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:42.650
and you press the same keys
stroke on the same web page,

00:08:42.650 --> 00:08:44.770
chances are you'll get nothing.

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:52.820
Now, here is what many people
don't know, but the development

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:55.800
of screen reader
has a long history.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:58.130
Its history are
longer than 30 years.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:04.060
This is very complex software
that updates regularly.

00:09:05.310 --> 00:09:09.700
You can see your screen here
as something very sophisticated

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:14.921
rather than a program
that speaks randomly.

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:26.230
Although screen reader
definitely has many features,

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:33.930
we can't do everything without
support of developers and designers.

00:09:35.370 --> 00:09:39.810
This is why your role is key here.

00:09:39.810 --> 00:09:42.200
You have a crucial role here.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:49.590
In my opinion,
there are three reasons

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:54.600
for which you should start
implementing accessibility standards

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:56.010
into your future projects.

00:09:57.230 --> 00:10:00.250
First, money talks.

00:10:00.250 --> 00:10:05.110
I won't go for details for
statistics today, but it's proven

00:10:05.110 --> 00:10:09.355
that accessible web
stores and websites

00:10:09.356 --> 00:10:13.070
actually generate much more profit

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:17.440
in comparison with their
counterparts that are not accessible.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:21.820
Second, gather visibility.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:26.900
If your website has perfectly
set elements such as headings,

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:32.600
buttons, checkboxes, et cetera,
the visibility will increase,

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:34.670
and more people will
know about the website.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:39.710
This is something that, say, your
experts can tell you more about it.

00:10:41.690 --> 00:10:45.710
Third, recommendations.

00:10:45.710 --> 00:10:49.960
If people with disabilities
see that your website is good

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.778
and they have a great
user experience,

00:10:53.319 --> 00:10:56.656
they will recommend the website
to their friends and family.

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:09.900
Now how does the inaccessible
websites actually affect daily lives

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:10.970
of screen reader users?

00:11:12.030 --> 00:11:13.350
